Backpacking may be changing, but it isn't dying

Stephen Meyers
stephenmeyers@coloradoan.com
0:41
1:08
AD
SKIP

Pick a weekend in the summer to visit the Rawah Wilderness and you're bound to run into them.

These fit, grungy hikers with sun-splashed hair and dirt in their teeth, carrying brightly-colored, heavy packs on their backs and wearing mud-stained boots on their feet, all of them sporting smiles.

They're backpackers. Some say they may be members of a dying breed.

Old-timers will tell you backpacking reached its height in the whimsical 1970s and has been on the decline ever since. Technology and today's always-connected, always-working society has kept us perched at our desks instead of perched on rocks underneath the stars.

In a July essay first printed in Paonia's High Country News titled "The Death of Backpacking," journalist Christopher Ketcham said he's finding fewer and fewer friends to join him on his backpacking trips. Ketcham, who recently turned 40, said even when he lived in the adventure hub of Moab, he knew hardly any person younger than 40 who backpacked.

Backpacking is dying, the essay said, because young folks are too attached to their iPhones, Facebook, Twitter, and video games on HD TVs. Backpacking instead belongs to the true pioneers of the backcountry, backpackers now in their 50's, 60s and 70s.

Chris Doyle, executive director of the Adventure Travel Trade Association said in the essay day-packs now take an increasing share of the pack market while technical overnight packs are a declining percentage of total sales. People are taking shorter, more intense hikes and staying in lodges or cabins rather than carrying their temporary homes in a heavy pack on their back.

The Outdoor Industry Association, which tracks things like backpacking participation, found in its 2014 Outdoor Recreation Participation Report that backpacking had fallen out the top five favorite outdoor activities for adults 25 and older based on frequency of activity last year. Running, cycling, bird watching, wildlife viewing and hunting rated as more popular. Although overall backpacking participation numbers were up 4 percent from 2010, Americans aren't backpacking as many nights.

Perhaps the annual two-week vacation has gone by the wayside, but backpacking isn't close to its death, locals say. Especially among Millennials, despite the perception.

Gerry Cashman, a longtime backpacker and sales associate for REI, 4025 S. College Ave., said he's fitting more people than ever for backpacking gear, and in a wide age range.

Cashman, 67, is also a volunteer with the U.S. Forest Service, spending about 30 to 40 days a year on the trails in the Canyon Lakes Ranger District. The people he sees on the trail "fairly well represent" all age groups.

"I know it's just me, but I'm not seeing the decline in that age range," Cashman said.

Don't worry Gerry, neither is the Outdoor Industry Association.

Though the 2014 outdoor recreation participation report did not break down activities by age group, its 2012 study of the state of camping did.

The American Camper Report said 42.5 million Americans went camping in 2011. Of those, 10 percent represented backcountry/backpacking campers.

Thirteen percent of the backcountry/backpacking campers fell into the 18 to 34 age group, the largest demographic. The age 55-plus group was the next largest demographic at 12 percent.

According to Dennis Lewon, editor-in-chief of Backpacker Magazine, a 2012 Leisure Trends report counted more than 1 million 18- to 24-year-old backpackers, about the same number of mountain bikers and whitewater kayakers in that age group, combined.

Avid backpacker Darcy McKinley-Lester, a sales associate at Jax Outdoor Gear, 1200 N. College Ave., falls into that age group.

The 23-year-old has been backpacking since before she was walking, tagging along in a baby carrier as her parents went west every summer for annual backpacking trips in the Rockies. A Pennsylvania native, McKinley-Lester moved to Fort Collins a year ago after graduating from Penn State. There, she led weekend backpacking trips for students. Many of the students were first-time backpackers, some of whom grew up in Manhattan and had never seen the stars before.

"There are people where being away from their phone is really hard, but I think a lot of people really enjoy getting away from that. They feel stress-free, they don't have to worry about stuff," McKinley-Lester said. "Every so often you get a kid who is completely uncomfortable, but most of them adored it."

But backpacking is boring, right? It's just hiking and hiking and more hiking, followed by unpacking and sleeping on the ground and squatting over a hole to go to the bathroom, then re-packing and doing it all again tomorrow. Young people aren't into that are they?

"People are like, 'All you're doing is walking then camping, walking then camping?' Well, yeah, but you're seeing really cool things," McKinley-Lester said. "I think people who think it's boring don't do much outside at all anyway. I enjoy getting away from it all. Being by myself, in the wilderness. It's the physical challenge that's appealing too. How long can I walk with this pack?"

Going lighter

Increased participation in adventure racing and triathlons shows America's growing obsession with endurance feats and high-adrenaline acts, a far cry from the slow plodding and wandering of backpacking.

But backpacking has picked up its game and gotten sleeker.

"Fastpacking" is the new buzzword in the woods, as hikers drop the weight of their packs, shedding all but the bare essentials. A mix between mountain running and backpacking, fastpacking has become more popular among backcountry enthusiasts as the minimal "less is more" movement has spread from the running and nutrition communities to the backcountry folks.

For example, backpackers are ditching that two pounds from an extra set of clothes in favor of a two-ounce bottle of cleaning solution, Cashman said. And the gear itself — the backpacks, sleeping bags and cooking equipment — has gotten lighter. Some of the extreme fastpackers opt only for bivouacs.

"Most of us, we'd be carrying 40-to 50-pound packs in the 70s and 80s. You don't see those anymore," Cashman said. "Almost all of the backpackers I know, even those in their 60s and 70s, they are shedding weight. If you're over 30 pounds, you're considered a heavyweight."

As Doyle with the Adventure Travel Trade Association said, manufacturers and retailers are changing the type of gear produced and sold.

Mark Worley, overseeing the equipment rental desk at Jax last week, said the store doesn't carry the bulky 80 to 90-liter packs commonly seen on shelves a decade ago. More common now are packs in the 20 to 60-liter range, for one to three night trips.

"The gear you see today is just so much lighter and better than what we used before. It has changed backpacking and the way people approach backpacking," Cashman said.

A family affair

McKinley-Lester grew up backpacking with her parents. Susannah Wright's kids will grow up the same way.

A backpacker for 25 years, she and her husband started taking the kids on backpacking trips when they were just babies. Teenagers now, the kids go on backpacking trips with their friends when the family isn't taking its annual backpacking trips during the summer.

"We spend a lot of time talking and listening to each other on backpacking trips, and we get to experience stunningly beautiful places together," said Wright, of Fort Collins. "Also, it's a great thing for a teenager to realize they can carry on their back everything they need to be safe, warm, dry, well-fed, and very happy for a few days in the wilderness."

McKinley-Lester admitted her parents think the trails have fewer backpackers now than during their adventures of the West in the 70s and 80s, but she doesn't think backpacking is dying.

"It's just changing," she said.

CSU graduate and backpacker Lynn Spishak is just fine if backpacking's numbers are dwindling.

"Yay, less people out there," she said.

Xplore reporter Stephen Meyers covers the outdoors and recreation for the Coloradoan. Follow him on Twitter @stemeyer or Facebook.com/meyersreports.
